We recognize the sum as a geometric series with first term \(a=\frac1x\) and ratio \(r=\frac1x\).  Hence for \(\bigl|\tfrac1x\bigr|<1\) (i.e. \(|x|>1\)),

\[
\sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac1{x^n}
=\frac{\tfrac1x}{1-\tfrac1x}
=\frac{1/x}{(x-1)/x}
=\frac1{x-1}\,. 
\]

So the series converges to the rational function \(\displaystyle \frac1{x-1}\) for \(|x|>1\).
